---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";
import { Image } from "astro:assets";
import DemoNicebucket from "../assets/demo-nicebucket.gif";
import ScreenshotSimplechore from "../assets/screenshot-simplechore.png";
import ScreenshotBreakFree from "../assets/screenshot-breakfree.png";
import ScreenshotPumpUpNotOut from "../assets/screenshot-pumpupnotout.png";
---

<Layout title="Projects" description="Description">
  <section class="space-y-8">
    <h1 class="text-2xl">Work</h1>

    <p class="prose dark:prose-invert">
      I'm currently working as a full stack developer at <a
        href="https://www.viable.at/"
        target="_blank">viable</a
      >. I get to work with various technologies and frameworks simultaneously,
      which I really enjoy. Lately, there's been a lot of React, Angular, Spring
      Boot, and AWS.
      <br />
      Before I joined viable in 2023, I was a frontend developer at
      <a href="https://asqs.net/" target="_blank">ASQS</a>, where I
      predominantly used Angular. On some, very rare, occasions, I also got to
      work with Laravel.
      <br />
      I've also been trying to work on personal projects more over the last few years.
      Some of my favorite ones are listed below. ‚¨áÔ∏è
    </p>

    <p class="prose dark:prose-invert">
      <a href="https://github.com/nicebucket-org/nicebucket">nicebucket</a> is a
      fast, private, and open-source GUI for S3-compatible storages. ü™£
      <br />
      I created it with my good friend <a href="https://github.com/itsboogie"
        >Philip</a
      > using Tauri and React. Tauri turned out to be a very interesting technology
      and a good fit for our use case. While the development would have definitely
      been faster with Electron (since we could have used TypeScript for the backend
      instead of Rust), I do not regret going with Tauri at all. The app feels snappy,
      the binary is fairly small, and getting back into Rust was a lot of fun as
      well.

      <Image
        src={DemoNicebucket}
        alt="Screenshot of nicebucket, a fast, private, open-source S3 GUI"
      />
    </p>

    <p class="prose dark:prose-invert">
      <a href="https://www.breakfreeapp.net/">Break Free</a> is an iOS app that helps
      people quit bad habits such as smoking, drinking or gambling. üôÖ
      <br />
      It is my first ever native app and I built it using React Native and Expo.
      Being primarily a web developer, this choice turned out to be a great fit for
      me.

      <Image
        src={ScreenshotBreakFree}
        alt="Screenshot of Break Free, an app that helps people quit their bad habits"
      />
    </p>

    <p class="prose dark:prose-invert">
      <span class="italic">SimpleChore</span> was an app that made it easy to schedule
      your meals and grocery shopping trips for the week. üçù
      <br />
      The stack I used to implement SimpleChore is Laravel and React, connected through
      Inertia. The frontend heavily uses Tailwind and shadcn/ui. I retired it in
      October of 2025, since it did not have any active users anymore.
    </p>

    <Image
      src={ScreenshotSimplechore}
      alt="Screenshot of SimpleChore, an app that aided in scheduling meals and shopping for groceries."
    />

    <p class="prose dark:prose-invert">
      <span class="italic">Pump Up Not Out</span> was an app and browser extension
      that helps people quit porn in favor of working out. üí™
      <br />
      It worked by redirecting you to the app whenever you try to visit a website
      with pornographic content. Once redirected, the app motivates you to do a quick
      set of pushups, pullups or squats. The tech stack was identical to SimpleChore:
      Laravel, React, Inertia, Tailwind, shadcn/ui. I also retired it in October
      of 2025.
    </p>

    <Image
      src={ScreenshotPumpUpNotOut}
      alt="Screenshot of Pump Up Not Out, an app that helped people quit porn and work out instead"
    />

    <div class="prose space-y-2 dark:prose-invert">
      <p>
        I've also had the chance to contribute to a few open source projects,
        which I think is a very cool experience. I'd certainly like to do it
        more often, but I try to limit contributions to issues I run into,
        rather than contributing for the sake of it. Some of most memorable
        contributions are the following:
      </p>

      <ul>
        <li>
          Adding a{" "}<a href="https://github.com/angular/angular/pull/47157"
            >configuration option to change the default date format of the
            Angular DatePipe</a
          >. This was my first approved to PR to a well-known repository, and I
          even got featured on the <a
            href="https://blog.angular.dev/angular-v15-is-now-available-df7be7f2f4c8"
            target="_blank">Angular blog</a
          >.
        </li>

        <li>
          Improving the (at the time) new{" "}
          <a
            href="https://github.com/laravel/react-starter-kit/pulls?q=is%3Apr+author%3Amatthiasweiss+is%3Aclosed"
            >Laravel Starter Kits</a
          >, since it was an exciting day with multiple contributions.
        </li>

        <li>
          Fixing the <a
            href="https://github.com/laravel/breeze/pull/348"
            target="_blank"
            >default value of a <span class="font-mono">useRef</span> call</a
          > in the Laravel Breeze starter kit, which was my first ever PR in the
          Laravel ecosystem.
        </li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>
